content.description: This route is marked by a cool crimp/tufa feature on a blank section of the wall about halfway up the route. Start up the route and work up the tufa before heading to difficult moves near the anchor.
content.location: Right of Unstable Behavior and Left of For Goodness Sake - look for the tufa feature.

content.description: Well flowing moves from bottom to top. Good'ish rests to keep the pump at bay but if you can't figure them out, good luck
content.location: 3rd climb from the right of the overhanging face

content.description: Moderate ledge climbing to a no-hands rest. More jugs await to another no-hands rest. Continue up on decent holds until you face off with "the move". Blast through the crux with a precise left hand into a sharp slot, and finish off on slightly dirty but good holds to the chains.
content.location: {Needs Location}

content.description: This is the left facing left arching dihedral on the very right end of the crag. Climb up layback and hand crack moves to the anchors of Nystagmus.
content.location: Far right side of the crag. Just to the right of Nystagmus.

content.description: A bolted chimney for the first half, then easy slab to the anchors.
content.location: Step up on a dirt ledge left of the main wall and head left into the squeeze chimney to start. The leftmost of three bolted climbs on the slab wall.

content.description: Its mostly easy slab except for a bouldery move at the 4th bolt as you leave the midway ledge. Then a little cryptic at the last bolt but a well protected crux.
content.location: Step up a dirt ledge left of the main wall. The first of three slabby bolted routes starting left of a hueco.

content.description: Start on the juggy arete and climb the crimpy slightly overhanging face. Save some juice for the crimpy crux at the top.
content.location: On the overhanging face this is the second route from the right.

content.description: A short blank section down low requires a bit of lock off and reach. Then enjoy relaxed and casual climbing above with plenty of good holds and rests to choose from.
content.location: Start at the top of the hill around the corner from Gas Huffer on the right of the two face climbs.

content.description: Steep pockets to a large move that gets you up to a shake before tackling a sustained run of slightly overhanging crimps and shallow edges.
content.location: on the left side of an obvious overhanging arete on the far left end of the crag

content.description: Starts with some large holds and becomes thin and technical.
content.location: All the way at the left end of the wall.

content.description: Hard moves lead to a sit down rest in a hueco before a pumpy run to the chains.
content.location: Route that goes to the right of huecco on main overhanging face.

content.description: Great climb on the left side boulders start. Sustained middle section tricky finish classic
content.protection: 8 bolts plus chain anchors. One bolt has a chain with a cleaning carabiner.

content.description: Fun pumpy climbing up the middle of the slightly overhanging pocketed face.
content.location: The 10th route from the right on the overhanging section of cliff.

content.description: Pull over  roof then climb up small pockets and edges to a balancy crux near the top.
content.location: Farthest sport route to the right.

content.description: Start on the first few holds of Diesel Therapy then head up and right. 5.10 pump leads to a fun run to the chains.
content.location: Just right of Diesel Therapy

content.description: Start off through some thin face holds and technical climbing up the dirty face. Reach the break and rest then take on the more friendly arête to the top. Seems to be cleaning up nicely.
content.location: Furthest left route on the main wall, just before the dirty, muddy slabs.

content.description: This route climbs up interesting pockets and edges. Slightly dirty now but should clean up nicely.
content.location: This route is the second bolted route from the right.

content.description: Start off a boulder in good holds but no feet due to the undercut roof start. But never fear, good crimps allow you to get established and get feet up. Crank great holds on steep rock and trend right as you head up the wall. A bulge midway serves up some cruxy moves. But its not over yet. Fight the pump clock on more nice pockets and edges to the anchors.
content.protection: 7 bolts, one fixed cable draw for cleaning.
content.location: The far left end of the main Coopers Cove, second route from the left.

content.description: Good slightly overhanging moderate climb. Has a nice rest at the halfway point.
content.location: Starts around the middle of the section of cliff where the low and wide ground-level cave is located.

content.description: Not the best route on the wall. Funky and slightly pumpy climbing.
content.location: On the wall just before the main overhanging wall.

content.description: Fun jug hauling to an interesting tongue of rock.
content.location: 8th route from the right on the main overhanging face.

content.description: Starts steep right off the ground, then becomes thin and slightly overhanging to the end.
content.location: Starts just left of the arete on the right side of the main overhanging wall, and just right of a short ramp.

content.description: Start left of the first bolt to take advantage of some back stepping on the wall behind you then trust your feet on the slab run to the anchors.
content.location: 10 feet left  of the main wall step up to a ledge. This is the second bolted route on the slabby face.

content.description: Awesome juggy start to the right of the first clip before some serious climbing. If you're feeling strong, the direct start goes at about the same grade. If you can keep the pump at bay on thin directional flakes, you can have this one in the bag!
content.protection: 7 bolts, 1 perma, to  anchor chains with clips
content.location: The line directly to the right of Road Kill

climbs.name: The Devil in the White City

content.description: (Have thoughts on this one? Send to me and I'll update it here.)
content.location: Starts on a really tall pile of cheater stones towards the left end of the low and wide ground-level cave at probably the highest point of the cave.

content.description: A short flake feature to the right of Work Therapy. Start in a bit of an alcove, traverse up over the bulge, and follow the flake to the chains.
content.location: Continue west (left) from the main Cooper's Cove wall, around to another set of routes. This is the flake feature before the first bolted route on that wall.

content.description: Tough start. Then moves through some steep rock on good edges and pockets.
content.location: Starts on some cheater stones at the left end of the 6-foot high, wide, ground-level cave.

content.description: Climb edges up a slightly less than vertical face.
content.location: This route is on the small east facing wall on the right side of Cooper's Cover that hosts this route and Sending in the Rain.

content.description:
Start the route and move through some sidepulls down low to move through the first couple bolts (consider stick clipping the second bolt). Continue on good holds to the ending where you'll have to pull on some tough crimps to gain the anchor clip.

I guess people really like this one and think it's one of the best at the wall, but I didn't think it was anything special.
content.location: Left of Pure Pleasure and right of Grab n' Go.
